{"atom_id":"ig34_p0284_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":284,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.3 Relating PP Records to PC Records","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"PC-PP Conclusions","heading_level":6,"sibling_index":7,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:03:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0284_a007","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":284,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.3 Relating PP Records to PC Records","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Relating the datasets (as described in Section 8, Representing Relationships and Data) is the simplest method; however, all time-point concentrations in PC must be used to calculate all parameters for all subjects. If datasets cannot be related, then individual subject records must be related. In either case, the values of PCGRPID and PPGRPID must take into account multiple analytes and multiple reference time points, if they exist.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["Section 8"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:03:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0284_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":284,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.3 Relating PP Records to PC Records","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Method A is clearly the most efficient in terms of having the least number of RELREC records, but it does require the assignment of --GRPID values (which are optional) in both the PC and PP datasets. Method D, in contrast, does not require the assignment of --GRPID values, relying instead on the required --SEQ values in both datasets to relate the records. Although Method D results in the largest number of RELREC records compared to the other methods, it may be the easiest to implement consistently across the range of complexities shown in the examples. Two additional methods, methods B and C, are also shown for Examples 1-3. They represent hybrid approaches, using --GRPID values in only 1 dataset (PP and PC, respectively) and --SEQ values for the other. These methods are best suited for sponsors who want to minimize the number of RELREC records while not having to assign --GRPID values in both domains. Methods B and C would not be ideal, however, if one expected complex scenarios as shown in Example 4.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":2,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:03:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0284_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":284,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.3 Relating PP Records to PC Records","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Note that an attempt has been made to approximate real pharmacokinetic data; however, the example values are not intended to reflect data used for actual analysis. When certain time-point concentrations have been omitted from PP calculations in Examples 2-4, the actual parameter values in the PP dataset have not been recalculated from those in Example 1 to reflect those omissions.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":3,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:03:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0284_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":284,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.3 Relating PP Records to PC Records","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"PC-PP – Suggestions for Implementing RELREC in the Submission of PK Data","heading_level":6,"sibling_index":8,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:03:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0284_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":284,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.3 Relating PP Records to PC Records","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Determine which of the scenarios best reflects how PP data are related to PC data. Questions that should be considered include:","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:03:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0284_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":284,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.3 Relating PP Records to PC Records","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Do all parameters for each PK profile use all concentrations for all subjects? If so, create a PPGRPID value for all PP records and a PCGRPID value for all PC records for each profile for each subject, analyte, and reference time point. Decide whether to relate datasets or records. If choosing the latter, create records in RELREC for each PCGRPID value and each PPGRPID value (method A). Use RELID to show which PCGRPID and PPGRPID records are related. Consider RELREC methods B, C, and D as applicable.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:03:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0284_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":284,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.3 Relating PP Records to PC Records","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Do all parameters use the same concentrations, although maybe not all of them (Example 2)? If so, create a single PPGRPID value for all PP records, and 2 PCGRPID values for the PC records: a PCGRPID value for ones that were used and a PCGRPID value for those that were not used. Create records in RELREC for each PCGRPID value and each PPGRPID value (method A). Use RELID to show which PCGRPID and PPGRPID records are related. Consider RELREC methods B, C, and D as applicable.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":2,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:03:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0284_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":284,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.3 Relating PP Records to PC Records","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Do any parameters use the same concentrations, but not as consistently as shown in Examples 1 and 2? If so, refer to Example 3. Assign a GRPID value to the PP records that use the same concentrations. More than 1 PPGRPID value may be necessary. Assign as many PCGRPID values in the PC domain as needed to group these records. Create records in RELREC for each PCGRPID value and each PPGRPID value (method A). Use RELID to show which PCGRPID and PPGRPID records are related. Consider RELREC methods B, C, and D as applicable.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":3,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:03:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0284_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":284,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.9.3 Relating PP Records to PC Records","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"If none of the above applies, or the data become difficult to group, then start with Example 4, and decide which RELREC method would be easiest to implement and represent.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":4,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:03:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"6.3.6 Morphology (MO)","heading_level":3,"sibling_index":6,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.6 Morphology (MO)","atom_type":"NOTE","verbatim":"Domain Decommissioning Update","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.6 Morphology (MO)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The MO domain has been decommissioned as of SDTMIG v3.4.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.6 Morphology (MO)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"When the Morphology domain was introduced in SDTMIG v3.2, the SDS Team planned to represent morphology and physiology findings in separate domains: morphology findings in the MO domain and physiology findings in separate domains by body systems. Since then, the team found that separating morphology and physiology findings was more difficult than anticipated and provided little added value. This led to the decision to expand the body system-based domains to cover both morphology and physiology findings and to deprecate MO in a future version of the SDTMIG. Submissions using that later SDTMIG version would represent morphology results in the appropriate body system-based physiology/morphology domain.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":2,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.6 Morphology (MO)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"For data prepared using a version of the SDTMIG that includes both the MO domain and body system-based physiology/morphology domains, morphology findings may be represented in either the MO domain or in a body-system based physiology/morphology domain. Custom body system-based domains may be used if the appropriate body system-based domain is not included in the SDTMIG version being used.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":3,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"6.3.7 Morphology/Physiology Domains","heading_level":3,"sibling_index":7,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a007","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.7 Morphology/Physiology Domains","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Individual domains for morphology and physiology findings about specific body systems are grouped together in this section.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.7 Morphology/Physiology Domains","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"This grouping is not meant to imply that there is a single morphology/physiology domain.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":2,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.7 Morphology/Physiology Domains","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Additional domains for other body systems are expected to be added in future versions of the SDTMIG.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":3,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.7 Morphology/Physiology Domains","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The CDISC Controlled Terminology of SDTM domain abbreviations and the therapeutic area user guides may have examples of other body system domains that are not yet in the SDTMIG.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":4,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.7 Morphology/Physiology Domains","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"6.3.7.1 Generic Morphology/Physiology Specification","heading_level":4,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.7.1 Generic Morphology/Physiology Specification","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"This section describes properties common to all the body system-based morphology/physiology domains.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.7.1 Generic Morphology/Physiology Specification","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"The SDTMIG includes several domains for physiology and morphology findings for different body systems. These differ only in body system, in domain code, and in informative content such as examples.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.7.1 Generic Morphology/Physiology Specification","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"In the partial generic domain specification table, \"--\" is used as a placeholder. In each individual body system-based morphology/physiology domain specification, this placeholder is replaced by the appropriate domain code.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":2,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.7.1 Generic Morphology/Physiology Specification","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"The variables included in the generic morphology/physiology domain specification table are those required or expected in the individual body system-based morphology/physiology domains. Individual morphology/physiology domains may included additional expected variables. All other variables allowed in findings domains are allowed in the body system-based morphology/physiology domains","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":3,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a016","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.7.1 Generic Morphology/Physiology Specification","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"All body system-based physiology/morphology domains share the same structure, provided here. Although time point is not in the structure, it can be included in the structure of a particular domain if time point variables were included in the data represented.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":4,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0285_a017","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":285,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.7.1 Generic Morphology/Physiology Specification","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"CDISC Controlled Terminology includes codelists for TEST and TESTCD values for each body-system based domain.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":5,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T10:04:00Z"}}
